  "local_port": 48676,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What IDE do you use for C/C++?",
  "response": "When it comes to C/C++ development, there are several excellent Integrated Development Environments (IDEs) available. My recommendation would be Visual Studio Code (VS Code) with the appropriate extensions. Here's why:\n\n1. Cross-platform: VS Code works on Windows, macOS, and Linux, making it a versatile choice for C/C++ development across different operating systems.\n\n2. Lightweight: Compared to some other IDEs, VS Code is relatively lightweight and fast, which can be beneficial for development efficiency.\n\n3. Extensibility: VS Code's power comes from its extensive ecosystem of extensions. For C/C++, the \"C/C++\" extension by Microsoft is particularly useful.\n\n4. IntelliSense: The C/C++ extension provides IntelliSense features like code completion, function signature help, and quick info for variables and functions.\n\n5. Debugging: VS Code offers robust debugging capabilities for C/C++, including support for GDB and LLDB debuggers.\n\n6. Version control integration: VS Code has excellent integration with Git and other version control systems, which is crucial for collaborative development.\n\n7. Customizability: VS Code allows for extensive customization through settings and extensions, enabling developers to tailor their environment to their specific needs.\n\nTo set up VS Code for C/C++ development:\n\n1. Install VS Code from the official website.\n2. Install the \"C/C++\" extension by Microsoft from the VS Code Extensions Marketplace.\n3. Install a C/C++ compiler for your system (e.g., GCC for Linux/macOS, MinGW for Windows).\n4. Configure your tasks.json and launch.json files for building and debugging your projects.\n\nWhile VS Code is my top recommendation, other notable IDEs for C/C++ include:\n\n- CLion by JetBrains\n- Visual Studio (for Windows development)\n- Xcode (for macOS development)\n- Eclipse with CDT (Cross-platform)\n\nEach of these has its strengths, but VS Code offers a great balance of features, performance, and flexibility for C/C++ development across different platforms.",
